('ACL Phase 1: Quad Set',
 'quads', array['knee_extensors'], array['quads'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['bodyweight','rolled_towel'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie on back with a rolled towel under the knee creating slight flexion (~10-20°). Tighten the quadriceps by pressing the back of the knee into the towel — do not let the heel lift off the surface. Hold 10 seconds, release, repeat. This is the most fundamental post-ACL exercise for re-establishing quad activation which is neurologically inhibited after knee injury/surgery. Begin Day 1 post-op.',
 'Activating hamstrings instead of quads; holding breath; allowing heel to lift; pressing too hard causing pain at the surgical site; not performing enough sets daily.',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Think about straightening your knee against the towel','You should feel your kneecap move upward slightly','Gentle: this is activation, not strength','Daily goal: 3-5 sessions of 10 reps throughout the day'],
 array['Terminal knee extension with band','Straight leg raise','Short arc quad with towel'],
 array['Quad set without towel on flat surface','Isometric quad contraction at full extension','Electrical stimulation of quad alongside quad set'],
 array['ACL','rehab','quad_activation','post_surgical','phase1','knee'], array['active_surgical_wound','severe_swelling'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', true, 3, 10, null, 30, true),

('ACL Phase 1: Heel Slides',
 'hamstrings', array['hip_flexors','knee_flexors'], array['hamstrings','hip_flexors'],
 'rehab', 'mobility', array['bodyweight','smooth_surface'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie on back on a smooth surface. Slide heel toward buttocks by bending the knee. Slide to comfortable range (never force). Hold at end range 2 seconds, slide back. Goal: regain knee flexion range of motion early post-surgery. Progress: increase range by 5-10° per week. Target: 90° by week 2, 120° by week 4. Use a plastic bag under foot on carpet to reduce friction.',
 'Forcing range beyond pain level; recruiting hip to compensate; not tracking progress with a goniometer; stopping too early when 90° is achieved (full ROM target is usually 135°+).',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Slide until you feel a stretch, not pain','Heel, not the whole leg: isolate knee flexion','Mark your progress: measure your bend each session','Gravity assists: you can use gravity (let leg fall) at later stages'],
 array['Active-assisted knee flexion in sitting','Standing knee flexion with support','Cycle machine at low resistance for ROM'],
 array['Passive heel slides with therapist assistance','Gravity-assisted knee bend hanging off bed edge','TENS for pain control allowing greater range'],
 array['ACL','rehab','knee_flexion','ROM','post_surgical','phase1'], array['active_hemarthrosis_severe'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', true, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('ACL Phase 1: Straight Leg Raise',
 'quads', array['hip_flexors','core'], array['quads','hip_flexors'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie on back. Tighten the quad of the injured leg (quad set first — this locks the knee). Lift the straight leg to the height of the bent opposite knee (about 45°). Hold 2 seconds. Lower slowly. The key: quad must be engaged before the lift — this prevents the knee from buckling during the movement. Precondition: quad must be able to hold a sustained quad set before attempting SLR.',
 'Lifting without prior quad activation (knee can buckle); swinging the leg rather than controlled lift; not reaching full height; arching the lower back; skipping this because it feels too easy (it is a fundamental building block).',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Quad set FIRST: lock the knee before you lift','Slow up, slow down: 3 counts each way','Hold at the top: 2-second pause','No arc: the leg goes straight up, not sideways'],
 array['Straight leg raise with ankle weight','SLR with resistance band','Hip flexion resisted standing'],
 array['Quad set practice alone','Supine knee extension isometric','Quad set with electrical stim for biofeedback'],
 array['ACL','rehab','straight_leg_raise','quad_strength','phase1','knee'], array['quad_lag_significant','acute_post_op_day1'],
 'push', 'sagittal', true, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('ACL Phase 1: Terminal Knee Extension with Band',
 'quads', array['knee_extensors','VMO'], array['quads'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands'], 'beginner', false,
 'Attach band to anchor behind you at knee height. Step forward to create tension with band behind the knee. Stand with slight knee bend. Extend the knee against the band resistance to full extension. The band provides an anterior force on the tibia replicating what ACL would resist — trains quad in a functional closed-chain position. Start: 3x15 at low resistance. VMO bias: ensure full extension with slight terminal extension squeeze.',
 'Not achieving full extension at the end range (stops at 10°); too much resistance causing pain; losing hip position and leaning forward; not engaging VMO (the inner quad that controls patellar tracking).',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Lock out fully: the last 10° of extension is the goal','VMO fires at full extension: that little inner quad matters','Resistance is light: this is early phase rehab','Stand tall: don''t lean forward into the band'],
 array['Terminal knee extension with higher band resistance','Single-leg press 0-60° range','Mini squat 0-45° range'],
 array['Quad set lying down','Straight leg raise','Seated knee extension machine (limited range)'],
 array['ACL','rehab','TKE','VMO','quad_activation','phase1','band'], array['acute_graft_site_pain'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', true, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('ACL Phase 2: Mini Squat (0-45 Degrees)',
 'quads', array['glutes','hamstrings'], array['quads','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['bodyweight','wall'], 'beginner', true,
 'Stand beside a wall for support if needed. Squat only to 45° of knee flexion. Focus on: (1) Knee over second toe (not caving in). (2) Weight through heel and mid-foot. (3) Equal weight both legs initially, then progress to more load on injured side. (4) Slow descent (3 seconds), pause at 45°, drive up. The mini squat range (0-45°) is ACL-safe — it loads the quad without excessive posterior shear.',
 'Knee diving inward (valgus collapse — most important correction); weight on toes; going deeper than 45° too soon; equal weight not being progressed toward unilateral loading.',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Knee over toe: second toe is the alignment target','Heel down: weight in your heel throughout','45° only: no deeper until cleared','Equal weight → 60% injured side: progress weekly'],
 array['Squat to 60° then 90°','Single-leg mini squat','Step-up low height'],
 array['Sit-to-stand with chair assist','Leg press 0-45° range','Wall slide mini squat with support'],
 array['ACL','rehab','mini_squat','phase2','knee','closed_chain'], array['graft_site_acute_pain','<4_weeks_post_op'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 3, 15, null, 45, true),

('ACL Phase 2: Step-Up (Low)',
 'quads', array['glutes','hamstrings','calves'], array['quads','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['step','box'], 'beginner', true,
 'Step height: 10-15cm initially, increase to 20cm then 30cm as strength improves. Step up with injured leg leading. Drive through the heel of the step leg to stand. Step down slowly (3 seconds). Focus: knee tracking, no Trendelenburg (hip drop). Progress: step height, then add weight, then increase pace. The forward step-up and lateral step-up address different hip stabilizer patterns.',
 'Hip dropping on the supporting leg; knee caving inward on the step leg; using the trailing leg to push off; step height too high before adequate strength.',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Step up: drive through the heel, not the toe','Knee: tracks over second toe throughout','Hip level: no dropping on either side','Step down slow: the eccentric is more important than the concentric'],
 array['Step-up with weight (dumbbell or vest)','Step-up to 30cm height','Lateral step-up for hip abductor emphasis'],
 array['Mini squat for baseline strength','Sit-to-stand for basic quad loading','Step-up to 5cm height'],
 array['ACL','rehab','step_up','phase2','functional_strength','knee'], array['<6_weeks_post_op','graft_site_acute'],
 'push', 'sagittal', true, 3, 12, null, 45, true),

('ACL Phase 2: Wall Squat (Isometric)',
 'quads', array['glutes','hamstrings'], array['quads','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['wall'], 'beginner', true,
 'Stand with back against wall. Slide down to 60-90° of knee flexion. Hold position for 30-60 seconds. Focus on equal weight both legs. Can progress: (1) Increase angle toward 90°. (2) Increase hold duration. (3) Add load (ball between knees, arms crossed). The wall squat develops isometric quad and glute endurance at functional angles — used as a screening tool for quad symmetry.',
 'Going below 90° (increases patellofemoral load uncomfortably for post-op); unequal weighting; feet too far from wall (changes angle); not maintaining neutral knee-foot alignment.',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Find your working angle: 60-90° as tolerated','Level hips: equal weight both sides','Hold and breathe: isometric endurance is the goal','Feet forward enough: shins roughly vertical'],
 array['Wall squat with ball squeeze between knees','Wall squat to single-leg hold','Progression to free-standing squat'],
 array['Mini squat 0-45°','Partial wall slide','Sit-to-stand practice'],
 array['ACL','rehab','wall_squat','isometric','phase2','quad_endurance'], array['acute_patellofemoral_pain'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 3, null, 45, 60, true),

('ACL Phase 2: Stationary Bike (Low Resistance)',
 'quads', array['hamstrings','glutes','calves'], array['quads','hamstrings','glutes'],
 'rehab', 'cardio', array['stationary_bike'], 'beginner', false,
 'Stationary cycling is the primary aerobic rehabilitation tool for ACL recovery. Adjust seat height so knee reaches only 90° of flexion. Begin: 10-15 minutes at minimal resistance, zero tension. Focus on smooth circular pedalling — the injured leg must push equally. Progress: duration (→45 min), resistance, cadence. No standing out of the saddle. Cycling maintains cardiovascular fitness while protecting the healing graft.',
 'Seat too low causing greater than 90° flexion (early phase); asymmetric pedalling favoring the non-injured leg; progressing resistance too fast; using this as replacement for all rehabilitation exercises.',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Equal push from both legs: listen to your body','Seat high enough: no more than 90° of knee bend','Zero resistance first: just movement and blood flow','This is your cardio rehabilitation lifeline'],
 array['Outdoor cycling at low intensity','Stationary bike with moderate resistance','Cycling on hill terrain at Phase 4'],
 array['Pool walking for low-impact cardio','Seated arm ergometer for upper body conditioning','Upper body HIIT during early recovery'],
 array['ACL','rehab','cycling','cardio','ROM','phase2','fitness_maintenance'], array['<3_weeks_post_op','wound_healing'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 900, null, true),

('ACL Phase 3: Single-Leg Press (60-90 Degrees)',
 'quads', array['glutes','hamstrings'], array['quads','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['leg_press_machine'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Leg press machine, one leg. Set safety stops at 60° minimum. Press through heel. Range: 60-90° (no deeper in early phase — ACL graft is vulnerable at deep flexion angles). Start: 3x12-15 at light load. Progress: add weight when movement is controlled and pain-free. Compare: injured vs non-injured leg output — target 70-80% symmetry before progressing to bilateral squat.',
 'Using too much weight too early; going beyond 90° before cleared; pushing through the toe rather than heel; testing strength limits rather than rebuilding progressively.',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Heel contact: push through your heel to target glute/quad','Range: never past 90° until cleared by physio','Compare sides: can you press equal loads?','Weight is earned: only add load when movement is perfect'],
 array['Single-leg squat to parallel','Bulgarian split squat','Step-down eccentric training'],
 array['Bilateral leg press','Mini squat','Wall squat progression'],
 array['ACL','rehab','leg_press','single_leg','phase3','strength'], array['<8_weeks_post_op'],
 'push', 'sagittal', true, 3, 12, null, 60, true),

('ACL Phase 3: Step Down (Eccentric Control)',
 'quads', array['glutes','hip_stabilisers'], array['quads','glutes'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['step','box'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Stand on a step (15-20cm). Slowly lower the non-step foot toward the floor — 5-second lowering. The step leg controls the entire descent. Touch the floor lightly, drive back up. This eccentric step-down is more demanding than the step-up and directly tests the quad strength needed for landing and deceleration — critical ACL re-injury prevention skills.',
 'Hip dropping on the stance leg (Trendelenburg); knee caving inward; rushing the eccentric; using the descending foot as a support rather than lightly touching; step too high for current strength.',
 'ACL_rehab', array['5-second lower: slow is the point — eccentric control is ACL protection','Hip level: no dropping on either side','Knee tracks over toe: consistent throughout','Light touch: the descending foot barely grazes the floor'],
 array['Step-down to 30cm height','Step-down with vest or hand weights','Running deceleration drills at Phase 4'],
 array['Step-up 15cm for concentric first','Mini squat 0-60°','Wall squat for isometric base'],
 array['ACL','rehab','step_down','eccentric','phase3','quad_strength','deceleration'], array['<8_weeks_post_op'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', true, 3, 10, null, 60, true),

('ACL Phase 3: Hip Strengthening (Abductor)',
 'hip_abductors', array['glutes','TFL'], array['hip_abductors','glutes'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Clamshell series and sidelying hip abduction. (1) Clamshell: side lying, knees bent 90°, open knees like a clamshell 3x20 each side. (2) Sidelying hip abduction: straight leg lift 3x20. (3) Standing hip abduction with band: foot slightly off the floor, raise 3x15. Hip abductor weakness is directly correlated with knee valgus collapse — the primary mechanism of ACL injury. Hip strength is non-negotiable in ACL rehab.',
 'Compensating with hip hiking rather than abduction; poor rotation control during clamshell; using too strong a band reducing range; skipping hip work because it doesn''t "feel like knee rehab".',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Hip rotation: clamshell opens the hip, not rocks the pelvis','Side lying: stack your hips — no falling backward','Band: light enough to complete full range','Hip strength prevents knee valgus: this work protects your graft'],
 array['Monster walk with band for functional hip abduction','Single-leg squat with hip abductor emphasis','Hip abduction during step-down'],
 array['Supine clamshell without resistance','Hip abductor machine seated','Passive hip external rotation stretch'],
 array['ACL','rehab','hip_abductor','valgus_prevention','phase3','glutes'], array[],
 'mixed', 'frontal', true, 3, 20, null, 30, true),

('ACL Phase 3: Nordic Hamstring (Modified)',
 'hamstrings', array['glutes','lower_back'], array['hamstrings','glutes'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['partner','pad'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Modified for ACL: ankles secured by partner, start in kneeling. Lower slowly 5 seconds to the floor — use hands to catch. Focus on hamstring eccentric control. Do not go to failure early: 3 sets of 5 reps only in Phase 3. Increase by 1 rep per week. Rationale: ACL grafts rely partly on hamstring co-activation to protect the knee — strong hamstrings reduce anterior tibial translation.',
 'Going too far too fast (progression must be slow for graft protection); not maintaining neutral spine; bending at the hips rather than the knees; performing too much volume.',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Slow lower: 5 seconds minimum','Knees only: don''t bend at the hip','Hands ready: you will need them','Progression: +1 rep per week, not per session'],
 array['Full nordic curl progressive protocol','Hamstring curl machine eccentric','Romanian deadlift light for hamstring endurance'],
 array['Supine leg curl with light resistance','Hamstring stretch and activation','Glute bridge for proximal hamstring'],
 array['ACL','rehab','nordic_hamstring','phase3','hamstring_strength','co_activation'], array['<10_weeks_post_op','acute_hamstring_strain'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', false, 3, 5, null, 90, true),

('ACL Phase 4: Straight-Line Running Progression',
 'cardiovascular', array['quads','glutes','hamstrings'], array['cardiovascular','quads','glutes'],
 'rehab', 'running', array['running_shoes','flat_surface'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Criteria to start running: (1) Full ROM. (2) No swelling 24h after training. (3) Single-leg press symmetry >70%. (4) Step-down without pain. Running protocol: (1) Walk 1 min / Jog 1 min x10. Jog at 60% effort. (2) Build: Walk 30s / Jog 2 min x8. (3) Continuous jog 20 minutes at 70%. (4) Continuous run 30 minutes. Only straight lines — no cutting or pivoting until Phase 5.',
 'Returning to running before meeting criteria; running on camber or uneven terrain too early; increasing pace before duration is comfortable; not monitoring for swelling after each session.',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Criteria-based not time-based: meet the benchmarks first','Straight lines only: no cutting in Phase 4','Run/walk first: respect the progression','Post-run check: is there increased swelling? If yes, regress'],
 array['Curved running at Phase 5','Figure-8 running drills','Agility ladder for change of direction preparation'],
 array['Walk/jog intervals at 50% effort','Stationary cycling for conditioning','Pool running (aqua jogging) as transition'],
 array['ACL','rehab','running','phase4','return_to_sport','progressive_loading'], array['<4_months_post_op','swelling_present','criteria_not_met'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, null, null, true),

('ACL Phase 4: Lateral Shuffle and Cutting Preparation',
 'hip_abductors', array['quads','glutes','calves'], array['hip_abductors','quads','glutes'],
 'rehab', 'explosive', array['cones','flat_surface'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Progressive lateral movement re-introduction. (1) Slow sidestep left-right at self-selected pace — 3x20m. (2) Resistance band lateral walk: 3x15 steps each direction. (3) Low-speed lateral shuffle: 3x10m each direction at 60% effort. (4) Figure-8 walk: 3 loops. Criteria: no pain or swelling after straight-line running. Purpose: re-train neuromuscular control for lateral movement before sport-specific drills.',
 'Crossing feet during lateral shuffle; insufficient hip loading (too upright); progressing to high-speed cutting before completing slow lateral movement criteria; no swelling monitoring.',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Athletic stance: bent knees, hip-width feet','Push off outside foot — don''t drag','Low and slow first: build speed over weeks','Swell check: 24h after session, no swelling before progressing'],
 array['Sprint cutting 45° angles','T-drill agility','Sport-specific change of direction at Phase 5'],
 array['Side-step without resistance','Clamshell exercises for hip prep','Lateral band walk stationary'],
 array['ACL','rehab','lateral_shuffle','phase4','cutting','agility'], array['<5_months_post_op','swelling_present'],
 'explosive', 'frontal', false, 3, null, null, 45, true),

('ACL Phase 5: Plyometric Return (Single-Leg Hop Tests)',
 'quads', array['glutes','hamstrings','calves'], array['quads','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'rehab', 'explosive', array['tape_measure','flat_surface'], 'advanced', true,
 'Standardized hop tests for return-to-sport clearance. (1) Single-leg hop for distance: max distance hop and land on same leg. (2) Triple hop for distance: 3 consecutive hops same leg. (3) Crossover hop: 3 hops crossing a line. (4) 6-metre timed hop: hop 6 metres as fast as possible. Limb symmetry index (LSI): injured/healthy x100. Criteria: >90% LSI on all tests before return to cutting sports.',
 'Testing too early before plyometric preparation; not comparing both sides equally; inconsistent testing protocol between sessions; treating 90% as the only criterion (strength, psychological readiness also required).',
 'ACL_rehab', array['90% LSI is a minimum: aim for 95%+','Consistent protocol: same footwear, same surface every test','Test both sides: injured first to avoid copying the healthy side','LSI is one test among many: not the only clearance criterion'],
 array['Return-to-sport running at 80% effort','Phase 5 sport-specific drills','Psychological readiness assessment (ACL-RSI scale)'],
 array['Single-leg squat for strength baseline','Single-leg press comparison','Step-down eccentric at 30cm'],
 array['ACL','rehab','hop_test','return_to_sport','LSI','phase5','plyometric'], array['<8_months_post_op_typical','LSI_<85%'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', true, 3, null, null, 120, true),

('ACL Phase 5: Agility and Sport Return Drills',
 'cardiovascular', array['quads','glutes','hip_abductors'], array['cardiovascular','quads','glutes'],
 'rehab', 'explosive', array['cones','agility_ladder'], 'advanced', true,
 '45° and 90° cutting drills for sport re-introduction. (1) Planned cuts: 45° cut at cones, 5m build-up, cut, accelerate 10m x6. (2) 90° cuts: same pattern with sharper angle x6. (3) Reactive cutting: coach points direction at last moment. (4) Sport-specific drill: pass and run, tackle preparation. Criteria: 90% LSI on hop tests, psychological readiness scale >56/100.',
 'Cutting on a stiff, straight leg (ACL injury mechanism — must land in athletic position); not following criteria-based progression; psychological fear overriding mechanics (if fearful, more preparation needed).',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Athletic landing: bent knee, hip hinge into cut','Trust your leg: sport is not safer than training','Reactive drills build confidence: progress from planned to reactive','This phase earns the return: don''t rush it'],
 array['Full training session with contact','Return to competitive sport','Season of monitored sport participation'],
 array['Planned cut practice at 50% speed','Straight-line running only','Agility ladder for footwork without cutting'],
 array['ACL','rehab','agility','phase5','return_to_sport','cutting'], array['LSI_<90%','hop_tests_incomplete'],
 'explosive', 'multi', false, 3, null, null, 90, true),

('ACL Prehabilitation (Pre-Surgery Strengthening)',
 'quads', array['glutes','hamstrings','hip_abductors'], array['quads','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','bodyweight','leg_press'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Pre-operative strengthening significantly improves post-operative outcomes. Protocol: (1) Quad strengthening: leg press 3x12, step-up 3x15. (2) Hip strengthening: clamshell 3x20, monster walk 3x15. (3) Hamstring: Romanian deadlift 3x10. (4) Balance: single-leg stance 3x30s. (5) Full ROM cycling 20 min. Research shows patients who arrive at surgery with stronger quads have faster recovery. Begin immediately after injury.',
 'Not beginning prehab immediately (waiting for surgery wastes recovery time); using pain as reason to do nothing (movement aids swelling reduction); not prioritizing quad strength specifically.',
 'ACL_rehab', array['The stronger you go in, the stronger you come out','Every week of prehab = weeks off your post-op timeline','Quad strength on injured side: measure it as your baseline','Pain-guided: discomfort is okay, sharp pain is not'],
 array['Complete prehab protocol over 4-6 weeks','Neuromuscular training prehab protocol','Sport-specific maintenance during prehab'],
 array['Walking program for baseline activity','Stationary bike for swelling management','Upper body training to maintain fitness'],
 array['ACL','prehab','pre_surgical','strengthening','injury_prevention','knee'], array['locked_knee_acute','hemarthrosis_severe'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, null, null, 60, true),

('ACL Neuromuscular Training (Perturbation)',
 'core', array['quads','glutes','hip_stabilisers'], array['core','quads','glutes'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['wobble_board','BOSU','foam_pad'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Perturbation training: therapist or partner applies unexpected pushes while athlete maintains single-leg stance. Progressions: (1) Double-leg on flat. (2) Single-leg on flat. (3) Double-leg on foam. (4) Single-leg on foam. (5) Single-leg on foam with perturbation. (6) Single-leg landing with perturbation. Develops the neuromuscular reflexes that protect the ACL — the muscles must react before the brain processes the perturbation.',
 'Progressing to unstable surface before stable surface mastery; too much support during perturbation (reduces the challenge); perturbations too predictable; insufficient base strength before neuromuscular training.',
 'ACL_rehab', array['React: you can''t think fast enough — your body must respond automatically','Start stable: earn the unstable surface','Perturbations: unpredictable pushes train real-world reflexes','This trains what protects your ACL — not strength, but speed of reaction'],
 array['Sport-specific perturbation training (e.g., basketball landing with push)','Reactive perturbation during cutting','Dual-task perturbation (cognitive + balance)'],
 array['Single-leg balance on stable surface','Tandem stance on flat','Double-leg balance on foam pad only'],
 array['ACL','rehab','neuromuscular','perturbation','balance','proprioception'], array['acute_post_op','swelling_present'],
 'isometric', 'multi', true, 3, null, 30, 30, true),

('ACL Return-to-Sport Psychological Readiness',
 'cardiovascular', array['core'], array['cardiovascular','core'],
 'rehab', 'cardio', array['bodyweight'], 'advanced', false,
 'The ACL-RSI (Return to Sport after Injury) scale assesses psychological readiness: emotions about return, confidence in performance, and risk appraisal. Athletes scoring >56/100 have significantly better outcomes. Coaching approach: (1) Discuss fears openly. (2) Graduated exposure to feared movements. (3) Cognitive restructuring ("my ACL is strong — stronger than before"). (4) Visualization of successful sport return. Incorporate throughout Phase 4-5.',
 'Ignoring psychological component (research shows it is the biggest predictor of second ACL injury); using time alone as readiness criterion; dismissing fear as "being a wimp".',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Fear is data: it tells you what needs more work','Re-injury rate doubles in athletes who return before psychological readiness','Confidence is trained: graduated exposure builds it','You survived surgery and rehab: your mental toughness is already proven'],
 array['Full competitive sport return','Sports psychology professional consultation','Graduated team training re-integration'],
 array['Visualization practice for sport situations','Watching sport matches for mental preparation','Light team training contact for re-exposure'],
 array['ACL','rehab','psychology','return_to_sport','confidence','ACL_RSI'], array[],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 1, null, null, null, true),

('ACL Long-Term Athletic Development Post-Return',
 'glutes', array['quads','hamstrings','hip_stabilisers'], array['glutes','quads','hamstrings'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['barbell','resistance_bands','plyometric_equipment'], 'advanced', true,
 'Year 1+ post-return maintenance program to reduce re-injury risk (which is highest in first 2 years). Monthly: (1) Nordic hamstring 3x8 weekly. (2) Single-leg squat 3x10 each. (3) Landing mechanics check: film and review. (4) Hip strength: clamshell/monster walk weekly. (5) Quad:hamstring ratio testing at 6, 12, 18 months. Re-injury rate: 25-30% in first 2 years without prevention program; reduced to ~8% with structured program.',
 'Thinking rehab ends at return to sport (it doesn''t — Year 1-2 is highest re-injury risk); dropping all specific work; not monitoring quad:hamstring ratio imbalance.',
 'ACL_rehab', array['Your graft is not your original ACL: treat it with respect permanently','Nordic curls weekly: non-negotiable injury prevention','Land well: every landing in sport is an ACL test','The 2-year window: highest risk, highest reward for prevention effort'],
 array['Elite athlete strength and conditioning program','Sport-specific high-load strength program','Off-season power development program'],
 array['Return-to-sport basics maintenance','Continued physio check every 3 months','Home Nordic curl program'],
 array['ACL','rehab','long_term','prevention','post_return','injury_prevention'], array[],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, null, null, 60, true),

('Knee Valgus Correction Training',
 'hip_abductors', array['glutes','quads','core'], array['hip_abductors','glutes','quads'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','mirror'], 'beginner', false,
 'Knee valgus (knee caving in) is the primary mechanism of ACL injury and patellofemoral pain. Correction program: (1) Awareness: squat in front of mirror, identify valgus. (2) Clamshell 3x20 each for hip ER. (3) Monster walk 3x15 steps. (4) Mini squat with band above knees: band cues outward pressure 3x15. (5) Single-leg squat with band: resist valgus 3x10 each. (6) Hip drop correction: side-lying hip abduction 3x20.',
 'Using the band as a crutch rather than a corrective cue; not addressing hip weakness (the root cause); squatting without feedback on valgus; ignoring the issue because it''s been there "forever".',
 'corrective_exercise', array['Knee follows the hip: hip strength controls knee position','Band reminds: push the band out with your knee','Mirror is your therapist: use visual feedback','This is a habit change: every squat for life should look like this'],
 array['Functional movement squat with full video analysis','Sports-specific movement correction','Plyometric landing with knee tracking emphasis'],
 array['Seated hip abduction machine','Lying clamshell for hip awareness','Simple squat awareness without band'],
 array['ACL','knee_valgus','corrective_exercise','hip_strength','movement_quality'], array[],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('Patellofemoral Pain Syndrome (PFPS) Protocol',
 'quads', array['VMO','hip_abductors','hip_flexors'], array['quads','VMO','hip_abductors'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','bodyweight','foam_pad'], 'beginner', false,
 'Runner''s knee / anterior knee pain evidence-based protocol. (1) Activity modification: avoid deep flexion and stairs temporarily. (2) VMO strengthening: terminal knee extension, short arc quads 3x20. (3) Hip abductor strengthening: clamshell, hip abduction 3x20. (4) Foot strengthening: arch raises 3x20, heel raises 3x20. (5) Taping: McConnell taping for pain reduction during activity. (6) Graduated return to running.',
 'Complete rest (weakens supporting muscles); too much emphasis on the knee without addressing hip and foot (root causes); returning to sport before pain-free with stairs.',
 'knee_rehab', array['Pain during activity: reduce load, not eliminate','Hip and foot: these drive the knee — address them','VMO matters: the inner quad controls patellar tracking','Stairs: pain-free stairs = safe to progress loading'],
 array['Running with patellofemoral monitoring','Cycling as pain-free cardio alternative','Hip-dominant exercise approach'],
 array['Activity modification and ice only','Unloaded cycling','Quad set and straight leg raise for baseline'],
 array['PFPS','knee_pain','runners_knee','patellofemoral','VMO','hip_strength'], array['acute_traumatic_knee_injury','locked_knee'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, 20, null, 30, true),

('Knee Osteoarthritis: Low-Impact Strength Program',
 'quads', array['glutes','hamstrings','hip_abductors'], array['quads','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','bodyweight','pool'], 'beginner', true,
 'Exercise is the most effective non-surgical treatment for knee OA (evidence level: Grade A). Program: (1) Aquatic exercise: water walking 20 min 3x/week (reduced joint load). (2) Stationary cycle 20 min at light resistance. (3) Leg press 3x12 light load. (4) Hip strengthening: band exercises 3x20. (5) Stretching: quad, hamstring, calf 3x30s daily. (6) Gait retraining: reduce ground reaction force. Pain: acceptable up to 4/10 during exercise.',
 'Avoiding all exercise (worsens OA faster than exercise); exercising through severe pain (>5/10); high-impact exercise before adequate strength base; expecting quick results (OA adaptation takes 8-12 weeks).',
 'knee_rehab', array['Acceptable pain: up to 4/10 during, 0/10 next morning','Move to manage: rest makes OA worse','Load gradually: joints respond slower than muscles','Water first: aquatic exercise builds confidence and reduces load'],
 array['Land-based strength progression','Strength training gym program','Nordic walking and functional fitness'],
 array['Pool walking only for extreme pain','Range of motion gentle program','Seated exercises chair-based'],
 array['knee_OA','osteoarthritis','low_impact','exercise_therapy','strength','pain_management'], array['acute_joint_effusion_severe','post_op_<8_weeks'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, null, null, 30, true);


