('Rotator Cuff Phase 1: Pendulum Exercise',
 'shoulder', array['rotator_cuff','deltoid'], array['shoulder','rotator_cuff'],
 'rehab', 'mobility', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lean forward, support non-injured arm on a table. Let the injured arm hang freely. Use gravity and gentle body movement to create small circles with the arm — not muscle-driven movement. 3 directions: circles CW, circles CCW, forward-back swing, side-to-side swing. 1 minute each. This early decompression exercise gently mobilizes the glenohumeral joint while reducing pain and muscle guarding. Safe from Day 1 post-shoulder surgery or injury.',
 'Using the shoulder muscles to make the circles (should be passive, gravity-driven); circles too large causing pain; leaning too far forward compressing neck; not doing enough repetitions (this should be done 4-5x daily early on).',
 'rotator_cuff_rehab', array['Passive movement: your arm hangs like a pendulum','Use your body to create movement, not your shoulder','Small circles: bigger is not better early','Daily: 4-5 times per day in early rehab'],
 array['Pendulum with light wrist weight','Gentle active shoulder ROM','Codman''s exercises progressive'],
 array['Completely passive shoulder rest','Ice and position of comfort','Gravity-assisted arm hanging with body support'],
 array['shoulder','rotator_cuff_rehab','pendulum','phase1','post_surgical','decompression'], array['surgical_wound_open','severe_acute_instability'],
 'isometric', 'multi', true, 4, null, 60, 30, true),

('Rotator Cuff Phase 1: External Rotation (Sidelying)',
 'rotator_cuff', array['posterior_shoulder','infraspinatus'], array['rotator_cuff','posterior_shoulder'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['dumbbell'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie on the non-injured side, injured arm on top. Elbow bent 90°, upper arm resting on side body. Slowly rotate the arm upward (external rotation) — palm moves from facing down toward the ceiling. Hold 2 seconds at top. Lower slowly. Weight: very light (0.5-1kg initially). This is the fundamental infraspinatus and teres minor exercise — critical for rotator cuff integrity after tear or impingement.',
 'Using too much weight (creates impingement shear forces); arm not pinned to the side (elbow drifts forward); going to pain rather than range; muscle substitution from other rotators.',
 'rotator_cuff_rehab', array['Elbow on hip: keep it pinned throughout','Slow and controlled: 3 seconds up, 3 seconds down','Zero pain: if it hurts, reduce range','This is the exercise most commonly skipped — don''t'],
 array['External rotation at 90° abduction','External rotation standing with band','Prone Y-T-W for complete rotator cuff'],
 array['Pendulum for pain reduction first','Passive external rotation range','Gentle gravity-assisted external rotation'],
 array['shoulder','rotator_cuff_rehab','external_rotation','infraspinatus','phase1'], array['acute_rotator_cuff_tear_full','post_op_<6_weeks_RC'],
 'mixed', 'transverse', true, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('Rotator Cuff: Internal Rotation with Band',
 'rotator_cuff', array['subscapularis','pec_minor'], array['rotator_cuff','subscapularis'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands'], 'beginner', false,
 'Stand sideways to anchor point. Elbow bent 90°, upper arm at side, hand pointing outward. Pull band across body — internal rotation. Hold 2 seconds. Return slowly. The subscapularis (internal rotator) is often the least trained rotator cuff muscle and is involved in many shoulder injuries. Avoid: too much range that causes anterior shoulder pain; band tension too high.',
 'Upper arm drifting away from the body; substituting with elbow flexion rather than shoulder rotation; too much range causing anterior impingement; not maintaining scapular retraction.',
 'rotator_cuff_rehab', array['Elbow on hip: pinned through the whole movement','Rotate at the shoulder, not the elbow','Controlled return: the eccentric strengthens too','Subscapularis: the forgotten stabilizer — don''t neglect it'],
 array['Internal rotation with increasing resistance','Internal rotation at 90° abduction','Subscapularis-specific functional patterns'],
 array['Internal rotation pendulum gentle','Passive internal rotation range','Gentle stretch into external rotation'],
 array['shoulder','rotator_cuff_rehab','internal_rotation','subscapularis','band'], array['subscapularis_tear_acute','post_op_<6_weeks'],
 'pull', 'transverse', true, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('Rotator Cuff: Prone Y-T-W Exercise',
 'lower_traps', array['rhomboids','infraspinatus','serratus_anterior'], array['lower_traps','rhomboids','infraspinatus'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['dumbbell','bench'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Lie prone on a bench or raised surface, arms hanging. Three positions: (1) Y: arms at 135° (thumbs up, lift to Y shape). (2) T: arms at 90° to body (thumbs up, lift to T shape). (3) W: elbows bent 90°, external rotate to W. Each position x15, 3 sets. These exercises target the lower trapezius, rhomboids, and external rotators — the most commonly weak muscles in shoulder impingement and rotator cuff dysfunction.',
 'Using too much weight (these muscles are very small — use 0.5-2kg for Y and T); not maintaining thumb-up position; lifting too high (only to horizontal); momentum rather than controlled muscle contraction.',
 'rotator_cuff_rehab', array['Thumb up: external rotation is built into each movement','Horizontal: lift to parallel with the floor — no higher','Weight light: start with 0.5-1kg for Y and T','Feel the squeeze between your shoulder blades on T'],
 array['Prone YTW with increased load','Full rotator cuff strengthening program','Band pull-apart and face pull integration'],
 array['Side-lying external rotation','Prone shoulder extension (I)','Seated scapular retraction without load'],
 array['shoulder','rotator_cuff','Y-T-W','lower_trap','impingement_prevention','rhomboids'], array['acute_rotator_cuff_tear','cervical_nerve_impingement'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('Rotator Cuff: Scapular Stabilization (Wall Slides)',
 'serratus_anterior', array['lower_traps','shoulder','rotator_cuff'], array['serratus_anterior','lower_traps','shoulder'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['wall','bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Stand facing a wall, forearms on wall (like push-up position at wall). Slide arms upward while pushing gently into the wall — this protracts the scapulae. Return to starting position. The serratus anterior is the most critical scapular stabilizer for overhead movement. Weakness creates scapular dyskinesis (wing scapula) which underlies most shoulder impingement and rotator cuff issues.',
 'Not creating pressure against the wall (loses serratus activation); winging the scapula during the slide (the opposite of what''s intended); rushing the movement; going too high causing pain.',
 'rotator_cuff_rehab', array['Push the wall: serratus activates under pressure','Smooth slide: no jerking or hitching','Protract: round your upper back slightly as you slide up','Scapular stability underlies all shoulder health'],
 array['Wall slide with foam roller on wall','Overhead press with scapular emphasis','Push-up with plus at the top for serratus'],
 array['Seated scapular retraction and protraction','Passive scapular positioning correction','Postural awareness training'],
 array['shoulder','rotator_cuff','serratus_anterior','scapular_stability','impingement','wall_slide'], array['nerve_injury_long_thoracic'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('Rotator Cuff: Sleeper Stretch',
 'rotator_cuff', array['posterior_capsule','shoulder'], array['rotator_cuff','posterior_capsule'],
 'rehab', 'mobility', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie on the injured side. Shoulder at 90° flexion (arm pointing forward), elbow bent 90°. With the other hand, gently push the forearm toward the floor (internal rotation). This stretches the posterior glenohumeral capsule. Hold 30 seconds. Tight posterior capsule causes GIRD (glenohumeral internal rotation deficit) — a primary factor in rotator cuff impingement and labral tears in throwing athletes.',
 'Stretching too aggressively causing pain; not having adequate trunk rotation (creates torque on the shoulder); pushing the shoulder rather than the forearm; using this stretch when posterior instability is present (contraindicated).',
 'rotator_cuff_rehab', array['Gentle pressure: this is a passive stretch','Feel stretch in back of shoulder — not sharp pain','Consistent: daily for chronic GIRD','Not for everyone: contraindicated with posterior instability'],
 array['Cross-body horizontal adduction stretch','GIRD correction program','Throwing athlete GIRD protocol'],
 array['Cross-body stretch with towel for less range','Passive shoulder external rotation stretch','Gentle pendulum before sleeper stretch'],
 array['shoulder','rotator_cuff','GIRD','posterior_capsule','sleeper_stretch','flexibility'], array['posterior_shoulder_instability','shoulder_hypermobility'],
 'isometric', 'transverse', true, 3, null, 30, 15, true),

('Rotator Cuff: Diagonal Pattern (PNF D1-D2)',
 'rotator_cuff', array['shoulder','traps','core'], array['rotator_cuff','shoulder','traps'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','cable_machine'], 'intermediate', false,
 'PNF (Proprioceptive Neuromuscular Facilitation) diagonal patterns for functional shoulder rehab. D1: hand starts at opposite hip, arc movement to reach overhead and out (like drawing a sword). D2: hand starts at opposite shoulder, arc down and out to opposite hip. Both patterns integrate multiple rotator cuff muscles through functional arcs — more specific to sport and daily tasks than isolated exercises. 3x15 each pattern each side.',
 'Too much resistance reducing range; not maintaining trunk stability during the diagonal; confusing D1 and D2 patterns; skipping this in favor of isolated work only.',
 'rotator_cuff_rehab', array['D1: think drawing a sword — diagonal from hip to above head','D2: reverse arc — from shoulder down to opposite hip','Smooth arc: continuous motion through the pattern','This is functional: these patterns appear in sport and daily life'],
 array['PNF patterns with resistance cable at higher loads','Sport-specific movement incorporating diagonals','Overhead reaching functional pattern training'],
 array['Individual rotator cuff exercises before combining','Light band D1 pattern for introduction','Shoulder ROM exercises in single planes'],
 array['shoulder','rotator_cuff','PNF','D1_D2','functional','rehabilitation'], array['acute_rotator_cuff_tear','post_op_<10_weeks_RC'],
 'mixed', 'multi', true, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('Rotator Cuff: Progressive Overhead Strengthening',
 'shoulder', array['rotator_cuff','traps','serratus_anterior'], array['shoulder','rotator_cuff','traps'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['dumbbells','resistance_bands'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Graduated overhead strengthening after rotator cuff rehab. Phase progression: (1) Shoulder elevation to 90° only: lateral raise 3x15. (2) Scaption (30° forward of lateral): elevation to 120° 3x15. (3) Full overhead with bent elbow (90/90): external rotation at 90° abduction 3x15. (4) Full overhead press: dumbbell press 3x12. Criteria to progress: no pain, strength >70% of opposite side at current level.',
 'Progressing to overhead before adequate base-level strength; using too much weight at any level; impingement arc (60-120°) causing pain without technique modification to manage it.',
 'rotator_cuff_rehab', array['Elevation to 90° first: earn the overhead','Scaption (30° forward): less impingement than pure lateral','Pain-free is the criterion: not time-based','Symmetry goal: match the opposite shoulder before overhead sport'],
 array['Sport-specific overhead movement','Throwing mechanics program','Full overhead press loaded program'],
 array['Side-lying external rotation for base','Pendulum for pain management','Prone Y-T-W for posterior cuff'],
 array['shoulder','rotator_cuff','overhead','progressive_loading','phase3_4'], array['full_thickness_supraspinatus_tear_unrepaired','post_op_<12_weeks'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', false, 3, 15, null, 45, true),

('Shoulder Impingement: Posterior Capsule Release',
 'rotator_cuff', array['posterior_shoulder','bicep_tendon'], array['rotator_cuff','posterior_shoulder'],
 'rehab', 'mobility', array['lacrosse_ball','foam_roller'], 'beginner', false,
 'Self-myofascial release for posterior shoulder capsule and rotator cuff. (1) Lacrosse ball: place between posterior shoulder and wall, lean into ball. Find tender spots. Hold 30-60 seconds each spot. (2) Foam roller: lie on side on roller at the back of shoulder. Roll slowly from posterior deltoid to mid-back. (3) Cross-body horizontal adduction stretch: pull arm across chest for posterior capsule stretch. 5 minutes total.',
 'Too aggressive pressure causing bruising; not breathing during holds; rolling over the actual shoulder joint (roll the soft tissue only); substituting this for therapeutic exercise.',
 'shoulder_rehab', array['Pressure: moderate — not white-knuckle pain','Breathe through each hold: the tension releases with breath','Soft tissue only: avoid the bony shoulder tip','Release prepares the tissue for exercise: do it before strengthening'],
 array['Soft tissue mobilization in physio session','Progressive stretch into horizontal adduction','Posterior rotator cuff strengthening after release'],
 array['Gentle passive cross-body stretch','Heat application for muscle relaxation','Pendulum exercises for gentle mobilization'],
 array['shoulder_impingement','posterior_capsule','self_release','lacrosse_ball','mobility'], array['acute_bursitis_inflamed','recent_rotator_cuff_surgery'],
 'isometric', 'transverse', true, 3, null, 45, 15, true),

('Shoulder Impingement Conservative Management Protocol',
 'rotator_cuff', array['serratus_anterior','lower_traps','shoulder'], array['rotator_cuff','serratus_anterior'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','dumbbells'], 'beginner', false,
 'Evidence-based non-surgical management for shoulder impingement syndrome (subacromial impingement). 12-week protocol: (1) Activity modification: avoid provocative overhead movements temporarily. (2) Rotator cuff strengthening: external rotation, Y-T-W 3x/week. (3) Scapular stabilization: wall slides, serratus activation 3x/week. (4) Posterior capsule stretching daily. (5) Gradual overhead return: scaption to full press over 8-12 weeks. Outcome: 75-80% resolve without surgery.',
 'Resting completely (weakens supporting structures); continuing painful overhead activities unchanged; not addressing scapular dyskinesis (root cause); expecting results in 2 weeks (takes 8-12 weeks).',
 'shoulder_rehab', array['Conservative management works for most impingement: trust the process','Impingement is not a structural problem — it''s a movement problem','Scapular position determines shoulder space: fix the scapula','12 weeks: that''s the minimum timeline, not the maximum'],
 array['Return to overhead sport','Shoulder strength program athletic','Full upper body training integration'],
 array['Activity modification and gentle mobility only','Pendulum exercises and ice','Gradual ROM restoration without loading'],
 array['shoulder','impingement','conservative_management','rotator_cuff','scapula','non_surgical'], array['full_thickness_rotator_cuff_tear','acute_bursitis_severe'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, null, null, 45, true),

('Shoulder Labral Tear Conservative Program',
 'rotator_cuff', array['shoulder','bicep_tendon','core'], array['rotator_cuff','shoulder'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','dumbbells'], 'intermediate', false,
 'SLAP and Bankart conservative management. Focus: dynamic stabilizers replace passive labral function. (1) Rotator cuff strengthening complete program. (2) Bicep tendon specific: supination curls 3x15 (SLAP specific). (3) Neuromuscular control: perturbation training in supported positions. (4) Proprioceptive exercises: single-arm weight bearing progressively. (5) Sport-specific positions gradually introduced. Criteria for progression: no pain in functional positions.',
 'Not modifying positions that stress the labrum (specific to labral location); ignoring bicep tendon involvement in SLAP tears; progressing to overhead throwing too quickly; not working on neuromuscular control.',
 'shoulder_rehab', array['SLAP: bicep tendon and superior labrum — load the bicep too','Dynamic stability replaces the labrum: build it','Position-specific: know your labral tear location','Return to throwing takes 6-12 months: patience is the intervention'],
 array['Return to throwing (baseball/cricket) program','Overhead sport return','Contact sport return program'],
 array['Rotator cuff basic strengthening','Posterior capsule mobilization','Pendulum and gentle ROM exercises'],
 array['shoulder','SLAP','labral_tear','Bankart','conservative','rehabilitation'], array['acute_instability','dislocating_shoulder'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, null, null, 45, true),

('Frozen Shoulder (Adhesive Capsulitis) Protocol',
 'shoulder', array['rotator_cuff','bicep_tendon','capsule'], array['shoulder','rotator_cuff'],
 'rehab', 'mobility', array['resistance_bands','bodyweight','pulley'], 'beginner', false,
 'Three-phase approach: Freezing (painful): (1) Pendulum exercises. (2) Pain-free passive ROM. (3) Gentle heat before movement. Frozen (stiff): (1) Passive ROM stretching all planes 3x30s. (2) Active-assisted ROM with pulley. (3) Gentle strengthening within available range. Thawing (improving): (1) Progressive active ROM. (2) Rotator cuff strengthening. (3) Functional movements return. Timeline: 12-24 months total natural history.',
 'Aggressive forcing of ROM in the freezing phase (increases inflammation); not managing pain allowing movement; skipping the gentle strengthening during the frozen phase; expecting quick resolution (typical timeline is 1-2 years).',
 'shoulder_rehab', array['Frozen: gentle is the word — force makes it worse in Phase 1','Thawing comes: every frozen shoulder eventually thaws','Daily gentle movement prevents worsening','Corticosteroid injection: consider in freezing phase for pain control'],
 array['Progressive physiotherapy intervention','Hydrodilatation procedure for severe cases','Return to full functional overhead'],
 array['Pain-controlled pendulum exercises only','Gentle warmth and gentle passive movement','Activity modification avoiding painful arcs'],
 array['shoulder','frozen_shoulder','adhesive_capsulitis','ROM','phase_based','mobility'], array['acute_freezing_phase_force_contraindicated'],
 'mixed', 'multi', true, 3, null, 30, 15, true),

('Post-Rotator Cuff Surgery: Early Phase Return',
 'rotator_cuff', array['shoulder','serratus_anterior','traps'], array['rotator_cuff','shoulder'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands'], 'beginner', false,
 'Post-surgical rotator cuff repair (typically at 12-16 weeks post-op). Transition from passive to active rehabilitation. Criteria: surgeon clearance, passive ROM restored, no pain at rest. Program: (1) Active-assisted ROM all planes. (2) Gentle isometric external rotation. (3) Gravity-eliminated rotator cuff activation. (4) Scapular stabilization: wall slides. (5) Pendulum discontinued — progress to active. Graft protection: avoid resisted external rotation against gravity for first 12 weeks.',
 'Starting active exercises too early (graft is weakest at 6-12 weeks post-op); ignoring surgeon''s specific protocol; aggressive self-exercise beyond pain-free range.',
 'shoulder_rehab', array['Graft protection first 12 weeks: passive only unless directed otherwise','Active-assisted: some help is provided — not full active elevation yet','Gravity-eliminated: exercise with arm horizontal to reduce load','Any sharp pain: stop and consult — you cannot feel the graft'],
 array['Full active rotator cuff strengthening at 4+ months','Progressive overhead strengthening','Return to overhead sport protocol'],
 array['Pendulum exercises early phase','Passive ROM maintained post-op','Sling use as directed'],
 array['shoulder','rotator_cuff_repair','post_surgical','early_phase','graft_protection'], array['<12_weeks_post_op_RC_repair'],
 'mixed', 'multi', true, 3, null, null, 45, true),

('Bicep Tendinopathy (Tendon Loading Program)',
 'biceps', array['shoulder','rotator_cuff','forearm'], array['biceps','shoulder','rotator_cuff'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['dumbbells','resistance_bands'], 'beginner', false,
 'Tendinopathy loading protocol for long head of biceps. Heavy slow resistance training: (1) Isometric: supinated curl hold at 60° 3x45s. (2) Slow eccentric: 5-second lowering bicep curl 3x12. (3) Concentric/eccentric (heavy slow): 3 up / 3 down, 3x10. (4) Functional: supination resistance 3x15. All pain-guided: acceptable pain 3-4/10 during exercise. Load: enough to feel working by rep 8.',
 'Complete rest (weakens tendon further); high-rep, low-load (tendons respond to load, not volume); stretching the tendon (increases compressive forces); returning to overhead sport before adequate tendon capacity.',
 'shoulder_rehab', array['Tendons need load: light weights won''t fix tendinopathy','HSR (heavy slow resistance): the evidence-based approach','3-4/10 pain during: acceptable — pain dropping each session','Patience: tendon collagen turnover takes 90+ days'],
 array['Full return to overhead throwing program','Heavy loaded eccentric curl program','Functional baseball/cricket throw program'],
 array['Complete rest with ice only','Gentle active ROM without load','Anti-inflammatory medication short-term'],
 array['bicep_tendinopathy','shoulder','tendon_loading','HSR','eccentric','rehabilitation'], array['bicep_tendon_rupture_acute'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', true, 3, 12, null, 90, true),

('Shoulder Instability: Dynamic Stabilization Program',
 'rotator_cuff', array['shoulder','core','serratus_anterior'], array['rotator_cuff','shoulder'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','bodyweight','wobble_board'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Multi-directional shoulder instability (MDI) or post-dislocation stabilization program. (1) Scapular stabilization: wall slides, serratus push-up 3x15. (2) Rotator cuff coactivation: all four muscles equally 3x15. (3) Rhythmic stabilization: therapist applies perturbations at different shoulder positions (simulated by partner). (4) Weight-bearing positions: quadruped, plank, push-up stability. (5) Functional reaching into all planes.',
 'Continuing activities that sublux the shoulder; strengthening only one muscle group; not addressing proprioceptive deficits; rushing return to contact or throwing sport.',
 'shoulder_rehab', array['Dynamic stability replaces passive ligament stability','All planes of motion must be trained','Proprioception: your shoulder must know where it is in space','Do not push into end-range instability positions early'],
 array['Return to throwing with graduated program','Contact sport return protocol','Overhead sport full return'],
 array['Posterior capsule stretching (contraindicated here — avoid)','Gentle active ROM in stable ranges','Pendulum for gentle mobilization only'],
 array['shoulder','instability','MDI','dislocation','dynamic_stability','rehabilitation'], array['active_dislocation','bankart_lesion_requiring_surgery'],
