('McGill Big 3: Modified Curl-Up',
 'core', array['rectus_abdominis','transversus_abdominis'], array['core'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'The McGill curl-up preserves lumbar curve (no flexion) unlike traditional sit-ups. Lie on back. One knee bent, one leg straight. Place hands under the lumbar spine to maintain its natural curve. Lift head and shoulders a few cm — just enough to create tension. Hold 10 seconds, breathe normally throughout. Sets: 3 x (6, 4, 2 reps) in pyramid. This is Part 1 of the McGill Big 3 — the most evidence-based back rehabilitation protocol.',
 'Flattening the lumbar curve (increases disc pressure); tucking chin to chest; raising too high (stress on L-spine increases); holding breath (dramatically increases spinal load).',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Hands under low back: maintain the curve throughout','Eyes to ceiling: chin slightly back, don''t lead with the chin','Minimal elevation: just a few centimetres','Breathe throughout: breath-holding spikes spinal load'],
 array['McGill curl-up with increasing hold duration','Functional curl pattern building to full program','Add curl-up to comprehensive core routine'],
 array['Supine breathing exercises for pressure management','Abdominal setting (transverse activation)','Diaphragmatic breathing for IAP development'],
 array['McGill','lower_back','curl_up','evidence_based','core_stability','rehabilitation'], array['acute_disc_herniation_severe','recent_spinal_surgery'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 3, 6, null, 20, true),

('McGill Big 3: Bird Dog',
 'core', array['glutes','lower_back','shoulder'], array['core','glutes','lower_back'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Quadruped position. Extend opposite arm and leg simultaneously — right arm + left leg. Hold 10 seconds. Return to neutral. Alternate sides. Spine must remain completely neutral throughout. The movement is done with the limbs, not the spine — the spine must be still. Squeeze the glute of the extending leg. This challenges the muscles that resist spinal twisting forces — critical for disc and spinal protection.',
 'Rotating the spine during the movement; lifting the arm or leg too high; losing neutral spine by arching or rounding; rushing the movement without the hold.',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Spine does not move: the limbs move, the spine is a rigid rod','Thumb up on arm extension: prevents internal rotation','Toe down on leg extension: prevents hip rotation','Hold 10 seconds then return: earn each rep'],
 array['Bird dog with longer holds','Bird dog on unstable surface','Standing cable bird dog for functional progression'],
 array['Quadruped holds (all 4 points, no extension)','Dead bug for similar pattern with less proprioception demand','Plank for core stability base'],
 array['McGill','lower_back','bird_dog','core_stability','rehabilitation','evidence_based'], array['acute_spinal_pain_severe'],
 'isometric', 'multi', false, 3, 8, null, 20, true),

('McGill Big 3: Side Plank',
 'core', array['obliques','hip_abductors','lower_back'], array['core','obliques','hip_abductors'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Side plank for lateral spinal stability. Lie on side, elbow under shoulder, feet stacked. Lift hips off floor creating straight line from head to feet. Hold 10-20 seconds. Breathe normally. Progress: duration, then add leg lift (top leg), then star side plank. The side plank directly challenges the quadratus lumborum and obliques that resist lateral spinal buckling — critical for disc protection against lateral shear forces.',
 'Hip sagging (not holding the position); shoulder shrugging instead of depressed; rotating the top hip forward or backward; holding breath; not progressing duration over weeks.',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Hip up: straight line from ankle to shoulder','Shoulder down: depress and retract, don''t shrug','Breathe normally: controlled breathing throughout hold','Build duration: start 10s, work to 45s over months'],
 array['Side plank with leg lift','Star side plank','Side plank with rotation'],
 array['Modified side plank from knee','Sidelying hip abduction before full plank','Supported side lying position'],
 array['McGill','lower_back','side_plank','core_stability','rehabilitation','obliques'], array['shoulder_acute_injury','cervical_pain'],
 'isometric', 'frontal', true, 3, null, 20, 30, true),

('Lumbar Disc Protocol: Prone Press-Up (McKenzie)',
 'lower_back', array['core','hip_flexors'], array['lower_back','core'],
 'rehab', 'mobility', array['bodyweight','yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'McKenzie press-up for posterior disc herniation (most common type). Lie prone. Place hands under shoulders. Slowly press up with arms — allowing the pelvis to remain on the floor. This creates lumbar extension. Hold 1-2 seconds at top. Lower. Repeat 10x. Assessment: does pain centralize (move from leg toward back)? Centralization during press-ups = positive McKenzie sign = disc responds to extension loading.',
 'Not allowing the pelvis to stay down (removes the extension loading); pressing up to maximum immediately (build gradually); continuing if pain peripheralizes (moves further into the leg — stop and consult); incorrect diagnosis (not all back pain responds to extension).',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Pelvis stays on floor: let your back arch','Pain moves toward the back? Good — centralization is the goal','Pain moves further into leg? Stop — this is not your movement','Gradual range: start small and progress to full range over sessions'],
 array['Standing lumbar extension against wall','Prone sustained extension hold','Lumbar extension in standing program'],
 array['Prone lying passive extension only','Position of comfort assessment','Heat therapy for muscle relaxation'],
 array['lower_back','disc_herniation','McKenzie','extension','centralization','rehab'], array['lumbar_stenosis','spondylolisthesis','flexion_bias_diagnosis'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', false, 3, 10, null, 30, true),

('Lumbar Flexion Protocol (Flexion Bias)',
 'lower_back', array['hip_flexors','glutes'], array['lower_back','hip_flexors'],
 'rehab', 'mobility', array['bodyweight','yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'For patients whose back pain centralizes with flexion (lumbar stenosis, facet joint, spondylosis). (1) Supine knee-to-chest bilateral: both knees hugged to chest, hold 30s x3. (2) Supine single knee to chest 3x30s each. (3) Seated forward bend: gentle hinging forward 3x30s. (4) Cat stretch lumbar: round low back and hold. Rule: if pain centralizes (moves toward back) with these exercises, this is the correct direction.',
 'Using extension exercises when flexion is indicated (wrong direction); not assessing centralization response; forcing range beyond comfortable; combining flexion and extension exercises without a directional diagnosis.',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Pain centralization in flexion = flexion is your direction','Gentle: these are mobility exercises, not strength','Consistency: daily direction-specific exercises accelerate recovery','Directional preference is personal: what works for you may differ from others'],
 array['Lumbar flexion functional movements','Full forward bending return to sport','Seated forward bend stretch progressive'],
 array['Knee-to-chest rocking gentle','Supine position of comfort only','Lying on back with knees bent (neutral)'],
 array['lower_back','disc_rehab','flexion_bias','McKenzie','stenosis','lumbar_mobility'], array['disc_herniation_posterior_flexion_worsens'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', false, 3, null, 30, 15, true),

('Glute Activation for Lower Back Pain',
 'glutes', array['hamstrings','core','hip_extensors'], array['glutes','hamstrings','core'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Gluteal inhibition is a primary contributor to lower back pain — when glutes don''t fire, the lower back overworks. Activation sequence: (1) Supine clamshell 3x20 each. (2) Glute bridge 3x15 — focus on glute squeeze, not just hip height. (3) Single-leg glute bridge 3x12 each. (4) Prone hip extension 3x15. (5) Hip thrust 3x12. Daily activation before any lower body training reduces lower back compensatory muscle use.',
 'Doing glute exercises without actually feeling the glute (hamstring dominant bridge); too fast removing the glute activation cue; treating as optional when it is foundational; skipping the single-leg progression.',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Feel the glute: if you feel your hamstring more, adjust','Squeeze: actively contract the glute at the top of each rep','Lower back flat during bridge: prevent lumbar hyperextension','Glutes protect the back: this is foundational daily work'],
 array['Hip thrust loaded progression','Single-leg hip thrust','Glute dominant deadlift pattern'],
 array['Supine knee squeeze with ball for activation','Prone glute squeeze isometric','Glute awareness exercise with biofeedback'],
 array['lower_back','glute_activation','rehabilitation','pain_reduction','hip_strength'], array['acute_lower_back_pain_immobilizing'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('Lower Back: Hip Flexor Release and Strengthening',
 'hip_flexors', array['lower_back','quads','core'], array['hip_flexors','lower_back','quads'],
 'rehab', 'mobility', array['bodyweight','foam_roller','resistance_bands'], 'beginner', false,
 'Tight hip flexors anteriorly tilt the pelvis, increasing lumbar lordosis — a primary driver of lower back pain. Two-part approach: (1) Release: kneeling hip flexor lunge stretch 3x60s each side. Foam roller quad and hip flexor 2x60s. (2) Strengthen: resisted hip flexion standing with band 3x15 each. Reverse lunge 3x12 each. Rationale: releasing tight hip flexors then strengthening them through range reduces the chronic shortening.',
 'Stretching without addressing anterior pelvic tilt posture in daily life; releasing without strengthening (creates passive hypermobility without control); not including lumbar neutral awareness.',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Stretch to lengthen, strengthen to control','Your hip flexors drag your pelvis forward: address this daily','Posterior tilt during stretch: tuck pelvis to maximize hip flexor length','Standing, sitting, driving: anterior pelvic tilt is the enemy'],
 array['Deep lunge hip flexor progression','Psoas release and strengthening program','Postural correction comprehensive program'],
 array['Seated hip flexor gentle stretch only','Lying knee-to-chest hip flexor positioning','Passive kneeling hip flexor stretch'],
 array['lower_back','hip_flexors','anterior_pelvic_tilt','posture','rehabilitation','mobility'], array['hip_flexor_strain_acute'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', true, 3, null, 60, 30, true),

('Lower Back: Lumbar Stabilization Progression',
 'core', array['lower_back','glutes','hip_flexors'], array['core','lower_back','glutes'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','bodyweight'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Progressive lumbar stabilization program. Phase 1 (stability): McGill Big 3 daily. Phase 2 (motor control): bird dog with band resistance, dead bug with contralateral arm/leg. Phase 3 (functional): half-kneeling chop and lift patterns, single-leg Romanian deadlift. Phase 4 (loading): deadlift technique, squat pattern. Each phase: 2-3 weeks before progressing. Criteria to progress: no pain at current phase, able to maintain neutral spine.',
 'Rushing phases; loading the spine before motor control established; adding load before pain-free at current level; treating all back pain as the same (disc, facet, stenosis all require different approaches).',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Motor control before load: earn the right to load the spine','Neutral spine is non-negotiable: if you lose it, reduce load','Progression is earned: criteria-based not time-based','Pain is feedback: 3/10 acceptable, 5/10+ means regress'],
 array['Barbell deadlift with proper technique','Olympic lifting with healthy spine','Athletic performance with full back loading'],
 array['McGill Big 3 only for foundation','Gentle walking as only exercise','Aquatic therapy for severe cases'],
 array['lower_back','lumbar_stabilization','progression','rehabilitation','core_stability'], array['acute_compression_fracture','spinal_cord_injury'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, null, null, 45, true),

('Piriformis Syndrome Treatment Protocol',
 'glutes', array['hip_external_rotators','lower_back','hip_flexors'], array['glutes','hip_external_rotators'],
 'rehab', 'mobility', array['bodyweight','lacrosse_ball','foam_roller'], 'beginner', false,
 'Piriformis syndrome: piriformis muscle compresses the sciatic nerve causing buttock pain radiating down the leg. Treatment: (1) Stretch: figure-4 stretch 3x45s each side. (2) Supine piriformis stretch (knee to opposite shoulder) 3x45s. (3) Self-release: lacrosse ball on piriformis 3x60s. (4) Strengthen: clamshell with band 3x20. (5) Neural flossing for sciatic nerve: gentle ankle pumping with elevated straight leg 3x15. (6) Hip strengthening: reduce piriformis overload.',
 'Aggressive stretching before ruling out disc herniation (same symptom pattern); not addressing the cause (weak hip muscles, tight hip flexors); confusing with disc-related sciatica.',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Piriformis or disc? See a physio: the treatment differs completely','Figure-4 stretch: most effective piriformis release','Neural flossing: gentle — not aggressive nerve stretching','Strengthen the hip to take load off the piriformis'],
 array['Hip strengthening comprehensive program','Return to running protocol','Seated piriformis stretch at work'],
 array['Activity modification only','Ice application','Gentle walking only'],
 array['lower_back','piriformis','sciatica','hip_external_rotation','rehabilitation'], array['confirmed_disc_herniation_L4_L5_S1','acute_sciatica_severe'],
 'mixed', 'multi', true, 3, null, 45, 15, true),

('Sacroiliac Joint Stabilization',
 'core', array['glutes','hip_abductors','lower_back'], array['core','glutes','hip_abductors'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'SI joint dysfunction treatment program. (1) Pelvis stabilization: active straight leg raise with abdominal brace 3x10 each. (2) Posterior oblique sling: single arm cable pull with opposite leg stabilizing 3x12. (3) Hip abductor strengthening for SI joint compression: clamshell 3x20, side-lying abduction 3x20. (4) Avoid: exercises that create shear across the SI joint (single-leg stance with trunk rotation). SI joint belt for temporary symptom relief.',
 'Exercises that increase SI joint shear (lunges, single-leg movements without adequate stabilization); not using SI belt during high-load activities temporarily; ignoring muscle imbalances in pelvic muscles.',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Brace before you move: abdominal contraction precedes every movement','SI joint needs compression: the oblique sling provides it','SI belt: helpful for short-term not long-term','Hip strength stabilizes the pelvis: build it systematically'],
 array['Full core and hip strength program','Running return with pelvic stability','Sports return with SI assessment'],
 array['Supine pelvic stabilization exercises','Gentle mobility without shear stress','Walking with SI belt for support'],
 array['SI_joint','sacroiliac','pelvic_stability','lower_back','rehabilitation'], array['SI_joint_injection_recent','fracture'],
 'isometric', 'multi', false, 3, null, null, 30, true),

('Spondylolisthesis Management (Conservative)',
 'core', array['lower_back','glutes','hip_flexors'], array['core','lower_back','glutes'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['bodyweight','resistance_bands'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Lumbar spondylolisthesis (vertebral slippage) conservative program. Focus: spinal stabilization without provocative extension loading. (1) Core: McGill Big 3 (avoid prone press-ups — contraindicated). (2) Flexion-based strengthening: hip flexion and extension in neutral. (3) Single-leg exercises: step-up, single-leg press for functional stability. (4) Avoid: heavy axial loading, hyperextension, and rotation under load until stable. Grade 1-2: conservative. Grade 3-4: surgical consult.',
 'Performing hyperextension exercises (worsens slippage); heavy axial spinal loading without adequate stabilization; treating as regular lower back pain without diagnosis.',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Extension loading: contraindicated — no prone press-ups','Core stability first: the spine must be protected before loading','Consult: Grade 1-2 conservative; Grade 3-4 needs surgical review','Load progressively: earn each new movement'],
 array['Supervised strength training within guidelines','Cycling and swimming as safe cardio','Functional movement training within restriction'],
 array['McGill Big 3 only','Walking program gentle','Aquatic therapy for deloaded movement'],
 array['lower_back','spondylolisthesis','conservative_management','core_stability','spine'], array['Grade_3_4_spondylolisthesis','neurological_symptoms_worsening'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, null, null, 45, true),

('Spinal Decompression and Traction (Self)',
 'lower_back', array['core','hip_flexors'], array['lower_back','core'],
 'rehab', 'mobility', array['pull_up_bar','inversion_table'], 'beginner', false,
 'Self-decompression techniques for disc-related lower back pain. (1) Dead hang: hang from a pull-up bar with feet not touching floor for 20-30 seconds. (2) Knee-to-chest traction: lie on back, hug both knees to chest, gently pull to create lumbar traction. (3) Doorway decompression: kneel, hold doorframe, sit hips back creating gentle traction. All techniques aim to reduce intradiscal pressure and relieve nerve root compression temporarily.',
 'Hanging too long before shoulder or grip strength is ready; aggressive traction causing more pain; substituting this for rehabilitation exercises; inversion table use without proper setup.',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Temporary relief: decompress then exercise to maintain benefit','Dead hang: allow gravity to do the work','Relaxation: the less tense you are, the more decompression occurs','This supplements rehab: not replaces it'],
 array['Assisted hanging program (arm strength building)','Professional traction therapy','Inversion table protocol'],
 array['Knee-to-chest stretch lying down','Supine position of comfort','Heat therapy before mobility'],
 array['lower_back','decompression','traction','disc','disc_herniation','pain_relief'], array['spinal_instability','spondylolisthesis_advanced','osteoporosis_severe'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', false, 3, null, 25, 30, true),

('Lower Back: Return to Deadlift Protocol',
 'glutes', array['hamstrings','lower_back','core'], array['glutes','hamstrings','lower_back'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['barbell','trap_bar'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Graduated return to deadlifting after lower back injury. Phase 1 (4 weeks): Trap bar deadlift (reduced spinal stress) 3x10 at light load. Phase 2 (4 weeks): Trap bar high handles to standard handles. Phase 3 (4 weeks): Conventional deadlift with Romanian deadlift first for hip hinge retraining. Phase 4: Progressive loading with form check every 10% load increase. Criteria: no pain at current phase, able to maintain neutral spine throughout.',
 'Returning to conventional deadlift too soon; using the "my back doesn''t hurt today" as clearance criterion; ignoring neutral spine breakdown under load; not using the trap bar transition.',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Trap bar first: same movement, 30% less spinal load','Hip hinge before load: perfect the pattern before adding weight','Film yourself: your spine position at 60% tells you more than how it feels','The deadlift heals backs when done correctly — avoid it and you delay recovery'],
 array['Heavy conventional deadlift program return','Olympic lifting after spinal recovery','Sport-specific heavy loading program'],
 array['Romanian deadlift for hip hinge pattern','Good morning for spinal erector endurance','Glute bridge for hip extension pattern'],
 array['lower_back','deadlift_return','rehabilitation','hip_hinge','progressive_loading'], array['acute_disc_herniation','<6_weeks_post_injury'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 3, 10, null, 90, true),

('Lower Back: Walking and Aerobic Rehabilitation',
 'cardiovascular', array['lower_back','glutes','core'], array['cardiovascular','lower_back','glutes'],
 'rehab', 'cardio', array['running_shoes','treadmill'], 'beginner', false,
 'Walking is the most effective and evidence-based exercise for chronic lower back pain. Protocol: (1) Begin: 10-15 minutes daily at comfortable pace. (2) Build: +5 minutes per week to 45 minutes. (3) Posture: upright, natural arm swing, avoid forward lean. (4) Nordic walking (poles): reduces lumbar load and improves core engagement. (5) Progress to water walking and then land cycling. Daily walking is more effective than 3x/week gym sessions for chronic LBP.',
 'Walking in painful posture (forward lean); choosing floor surfaces that worsen pain; using walking to replace all rehabilitation exercises; not building duration progressively.',
 'lower_back_rehab', array['Walking is medicine: daily beats occasional gym','Upright posture: natural S-curve, eyes forward','Surface matters: grass and soft track reduce joint impact','Consistency: 45 minutes daily is the evidence-based target'],
 array['Jogging return after walking tolerance established','Nordic walking for enhanced benefit','Trail walking for proprioception challenge'],
 array['Short 5-minute pain-free walks only','Pool walking for deloaded environment','Stationary bike for non-impact cardio'],
 array['lower_back','walking','aerobic','rehabilitation','chronic_LBP','evidence_based'], array['acute_severe_lower_back_pain'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, null, null, true);


