('Ankle Sprain Rehab Phase 1: RICE + Gentle ROM',
 'calves', array['ankle_stabilisers','peroneals'], array['calves','ankle_stabilisers'],
 'rehab', 'mobility', array['compression_bandage','ice'], 'beginner', false,
 'Acute lateral ankle sprain (most common inversion sprain). Phase 1 (Day 1-7): (1) RICE: Rest-Ice-Compression-Elevation. (2) Gentle alphabet writing with the foot (seated): maintains joint lubrication. (3) Gentle circumduction: ankle circles both directions 3x10. (4) Early weight bearing as tolerated after 48-72 hours (evidence shows early mobilization beats prolonged rest). Goal: reduce swelling, maintain range, begin proprioception.',
 'Prolonged immobilization beyond 48-72 hours (delays recovery); ice continuously (use: 20 min on/40 min off); not beginning early gentle mobility; returning to sport without completing the full protocol.',
 'ankle_rehab', array['Ice: 20 minutes on, 40 off — not continuous','Early movement: gentle, not forced','Weight-bearing early: walking on it (if tolerable) is evidence-based','Elevation: above heart level for first 48 hours'],
 array['Progressive weight bearing protocol','Balance and proprioception Phase 2','Return to running Phase 3'],
 array['Complete rest with ice only','Elevation and compression without movement','Non-weight bearing with crutches if Grade 3'],
 array['ankle_sprain','rehab','RICE','acute','phase1','lateral_ankle'], array['Grade_3_complete_ligament_rupture_without_assessment'],
 'mixed', 'multi', true, 3, null, null, 30, true),

('Ankle Sprain Rehab Phase 2: Proprioception',
 'calves', array['ankle_stabilisers','peroneals','tibialis_anterior'], array['calves','ankle_stabilisers'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['wobble_board','foam_pad','resistance_bands'], 'beginner', false,
 'Proprioception is the #1 deficit after ankle sprain — and the primary reason for re-injury. Phase 2 (Day 7-21): (1) Single-leg balance on flat surface 3x30s each. (2) Single-leg balance with eyes closed 3x20s. (3) Single-leg balance on foam pad 3x20s. (4) Wobble board: bilateral → unilateral 3x30s each. (5) Theraband resistance ankle alphabet 3x1 set each. All progressive — only advance when current level pain-free and stable.',
 'Skipping proprioception training (leads to chronic ankle instability in 40% of cases); too much challenge too soon (safety risk); not including eyes-closed (visual compensation hides proprioception deficit).',
 'ankle_rehab', array['Eyes closed: removes visual compensation — harder and more real','Wobble board is the goal: earn it progressively','Every session: start easy, progress to challenge','Balance training reduces re-sprain risk by 50%: do not skip'],
 array['Dynamic balance during sport-specific movements','Plyometric ankle conditioning','Return to sport agility drills'],
 array['Sit-to-stand with support','Single-leg stance with hand support','Double-leg balance on flat surface'],
 array['ankle_sprain','rehab','proprioception','balance','phase2','ankle_stability'], array['acute_phase_still_significantly_swollen'],
 'isometric', 'multi', true, 3, null, 30, 20, true),

('Ankle Sprain Rehab Phase 3: Strength and Return to Sport',
 'calves', array['peroneals','tibialis_anterior','quads'], array['calves','peroneals','tibialis_anterior'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','calf_raise_equipment'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Phase 3 (Week 3-8): Full ankle rehabilitation. (1) Calf raises: 3x20 progressing to single-leg 3x15. (2) Peroneal strengthening: band eversion 3x20 each. (3) Eccentric heel drops: lower slowly off step 3x15. (4) Jump rope: bilateral first, then single-leg hops. (5) Figure-of-8 running. (6) Sport-specific drills at increasing intensity. Return criteria: 90% single-leg hop distance vs opposite, pain-free sport movements.',
 'Returning to sport before 90% symmetry; not completing peroneal strengthening (the primary re-injury prevention muscle); starting jumping before adequate strength; neglecting taping/bracing for return to sport.',
 'ankle_rehab', array['Peroneals protect you: eversion strength is your primary protection','90% hop test: the return-to-sport criterion','Single-leg calf raise = single-leg running: test it','Tape or brace: use for return season even after full recovery'],
 array['Full sport return with taping','High-speed lateral change of direction','Ankle proprioception maintenance program'],
 array['Phase 2 completion criteria met','Walking pain-free baseline','Single-leg stance stable before hopping'],
 array['ankle_sprain','rehab','phase3','return_to_sport','peroneal','strength'], array['partial_ligament_repair_not_healed'],
 'mixed', 'multi', true, 3, 15, null, 45, true),

('Chronic Ankle Instability: Long-Term Prevention',
 'calves', array['peroneals','ankle_stabilisers','tibialis_anterior'], array['calves','peroneals','ankle_stabilisers'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','wobble_board'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Chronic ankle instability (CAI) affects 40% of initial ankle sprain patients. Prevention and management: (1) Peroneal strengthening: band eversion 4x20, 3x/week — maintenance forever. (2) Balance training: wobble board 3x45s single-leg, 3x/week. (3) Proprioceptive warm-up: balance drills before every training session. (4) Jump landing with ankle stability focus: 3x10. (5) Footwear and taping assessment: lace-up ankle brace for high-risk sports.',
 'Stopping rehabilitation after initial symptoms resolve (CAI becomes permanent if not maintained); not using prophylactic bracing in sport; assuming it will "just get better" after years of giving way.',
 'ankle_rehab', array['Maintenance: eversion strength training is for life','Balance before exercise: 2-minute warm-up prevents re-injury','Your ankle gave way because the peroneals failed to react: train them','Bracing + strength: both, not either/or'],
 array['Athletic performance with ankle stability foundation','High-risk sport participation with brace','Surgical stabilization if conservative management fails'],
 array['Basic eversion band exercises','Single-leg balance 20 seconds','Walking program with ankle awareness'],
 array['ankle','chronic_instability','CAI','prevention','peroneal','long_term'], array[],
 'mixed', 'multi', true, 3, 20, null, 30, true),

('Achilles Tendinopathy: Alfredson Protocol',
 'calves', array['soleus','gastrocnemius'], array['calves','soleus','gastrocnemius'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['step','bodyweight'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Eccentric heel drop protocol (Alfredson, 1998) — gold standard for Achilles tendinopathy. Stand on step edge, both feet. Rise up on both feet. Transfer weight to injured foot. Slowly lower heel below step level (5 seconds eccentric). 3x15 with straight knee (gastrocnemius). 3x15 with bent knee (soleus). Twice daily 7 days per week for 12 weeks. Pain 3-5/10 during is acceptable. This is the most evidence-based tendinopathy treatment in existence.',
 'Stopping when it hurts (acceptable pain is the goal — the exercise must load the tendon); too slow progression to single-leg eccentric; not completing twice daily (once daily = half the stimulus); using this for insertional tendinopathy (different protocol applies to the heel attachment).',
 'ankle_rehab', array['Pain during is acceptable (3-5/10): this is heavy slow resistance for the tendon','Slow lower: 5 seconds — any faster reduces the stimulus','Twice daily 7 days: this is the evidence-based dose','12 weeks: the tendon takes time — this is a marathon not a sprint'],
 array['Single-leg eccentric (both phases)','Heavy slow resistance protocol addition','Return to running after Alfredson clearance'],
 array['Swimming and cycling for cardio maintenance','Bilateral eccentric at lower range','Gentle calf stretching before starting eccentric'],
 array['achilles_tendinopathy','Alfredson','eccentric','evidence_based','calf','rehabilitation'], array['achilles_tendon_rupture','insertional_tendinopathy_different_protocol'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', true, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('Plantar Fasciitis Management Protocol',
 'calves', array['plantar_fascia','foot_intrinsics','tibialis_posterior'], array['calves','plantar_fascia'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','rolling_pin','frozen_water_bottle'], 'beginner', false,
 'Plantar fasciitis affects the fibrous tissue under the foot. Protocol: (1) Morning: before first step, do 3x15 seated plantar fascia stretches (pull toes back). (2) Intrinsic foot strengthening: towel scrunches with toes 3x30, short foot exercise 3x15 each. (3) Calf stretching: gastrocnemius and soleus 3x30s each. (4) Eccentric calf raises 3x15. (5) Ice massage: frozen bottle rolling under foot 5 min after activity. (6) Activity modification: avoid barefoot on hard floors.',
 'Ignoring calf tightness (primary driver of plantar fascia tension); not doing morning stretching before first steps (most important intervention); too much barefoot activity on hard floors; returning to running without addressing the underlying cause.',
 'ankle_rehab', array['Morning stretch: before your feet touch the floor','Short foot: scrunch your toes without curling them — builds arch strength','Gastrocnemius AND soleus: both calf muscles must be stretched separately','Ice massage post-activity: anti-inflammatory and desensitising'],
 array['Return to running protocol','Custom orthotics assessment','Night splint for overnight stretch maintenance'],
 array['Ice and activity modification only','Gentle calf stretching only','Non-weight bearing alternatives'],
 array['plantar_fasciitis','foot','rehabilitation','calf','morning_stretch','intrinsic_strength'], array['plantar_fascia_rupture_acute'],
 'mixed', 'multi', true, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('Shin Splints (MTSS) Management',
 'tibialis_anterior', array['calves','foot_intrinsics','hip_flexors'], array['tibialis_anterior','calves'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','foam_roller'], 'beginner', false,
 'Medial tibial stress syndrome (shin splints). Two types: posterior (most common — soleus/FDL) and anterior (less common — tibialis anterior). Treatment: (1) Load management: reduce running volume by 50%. (2) Calf strengthening: eccentric heel raises (Alfredson) 3x15. (3) Tibialis anterior strengthening: dorsiflexion against resistance 3x20. (4) Hip strengthening: reduces overpronation. (5) Foam rolling: calves and peroneals. (6) Running mechanics: reduce overstriding.',
 'Completely stopping running (deconditioning makes return harder); running through severe pain (risks stress fracture); returning to full volume too quickly; ignoring footwear (one of the primary contributors).',
 'ankle_rehab', array['Load reduction: not elimination — maintain some stimulus','Calf strength: the engine that causes and cures shin splints','Footwear: shoe age and type matters more than you think','Running mechanics: shorter stride reduces impact force 20%'],
 array['Return to full running volume progressively','Running mechanics coaching','Bone stress injury prevention program'],
 array['Complete activity modification','Walking only for maintenance','Non-impact cardio cycling and swimming'],
 array['shin_splints','MTSS','running_injury','tibia','stress_fracture_prevention','rehabilitation'], array['bone_stress_injury_suspected','stress_fracture_confirmed'],
 'mixed', 'multi', true, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('Postural Correction: Forward Head Posture',
 'traps', array['cervical_extensors','shoulder','rhomboids'], array['traps','cervical_extensors'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','wall'], 'beginner', false,
 'Forward head posture (head forward of shoulders) is the most common postural deviation. Correction program: (1) Chin tuck: retract chin (make a double chin) 3x15 x4 daily. (2) Deep cervical flexor strengthening: supine chin tuck + slight lift 3x10. (3) Upper trap and levator stretch 3x45s each side. (4) Band pull-apart for thoracic extension 3x20. (5) Wall posture check: back of head, upper back, buttocks all touching wall. (6) Ergonomics: screen at eye level.',
 'Forcing head back without neck muscle engagement (creates cervical strain); not addressing thoracic kyphosis (forward head follows rounded upper back); sitting ergonomics not addressed.',
 'postural_rehab', array['Chin tuck: retract, don''t just tilt back','The deep cervical flexors hold your head back: strengthen them','Thoracic extension first: fixing the upper back corrects the head','Ergonomics: an hour of daily work undoes 10 minutes of exercise'],
 array['Loaded chin tuck progression','Advanced deep neck flexor program','Screen ergonomics complete assessment'],
 array['Gentle neck stretch and mobility','Passive chin tuck with finger cue','Awareness training without strengthening'],
 array['postural','forward_head_posture','cervical','neck','corrective_exercise','ergonomics'], array['cervical_instability','cervical_myelopathy'],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', false, 4, 15, null, 20, true),

('Postural Correction: Upper Crossed Syndrome',
 'rhomboids', array['lower_traps','serratus_anterior','deep_cervical_flexors'], array['rhomboids','lower_traps'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','foam_roller'], 'beginner', false,
 'Upper crossed syndrome: tight upper traps and pec minor, weak deep cervical flexors and lower traps. Creates rounded shoulders, forward head, kyphotic thoracic spine. Correction: (1) Release: pec minor stretch 3x45s, upper trap stretch 3x45s, foam roller thoracic 2x60s. (2) Strengthen: chin tucks, band pull-apart, lower trap Y-T-W. (3) Posture awareness: hourly reset in seated position. (4) Breathing: diaphragmatic breathing vs accessory muscle breathing.',
 'Strengthening already tight muscles (upper traps); stretching already lengthened muscles (lower traps in their lengthened position); not addressing daily habits that recreate the pattern.',
 'postural_rehab', array['Release the tight ones first: pec minor and upper trap','Strengthen the weak ones: lower trap and deep neck flexors','Posture is a habit: reset it every hour','Diaphragmatic breathing: accessory breathing worsens upper cross'],
 array['Complete postural restoration program','Athletic performance posture program','Ergonomic assessment and workstation setup'],
 array['Passive stretching only','Foam rolling for awareness','Posture self-awareness only'],
 array['postural','upper_crossed_syndrome','rounded_shoulders','thoracic','corrective_exercise'], array[],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, null, null, 30, true),

('Postural Correction: Lower Crossed Syndrome',
 'glutes', array['transversus_abdominis','hamstrings','lower_back'], array['glutes','transversus_abdominis'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lower crossed syndrome: tight hip flexors and lumbar erectors, weak glutes and abdominals. Creates anterior pelvic tilt, lordotic low back. Correction: (1) Release: hip flexor lunge stretch 3x60s, lumbar extension self-release. (2) Strengthen: glute bridge 3x15, dead bug 3x10 each, plank 3x30s. (3) Motor pattern: posterior pelvic tilt awareness in standing. (4) Hip hinge retraining with neutral pelvis.',
 'Strengthening hip flexors without releasing them; doing sit-ups (worsens hip flexor dominance); not addressing sitting posture (recreates lower cross all day); not connecting exercise to movement patterns.',
 'postural_rehab', array['Anterior tilt: ribs up, pelvis tilts forward — visualize the bucket of water spilling','Hip flexors lengthen first: then strengthen the glutes','Posterior tilt: tuck pelvis, flatten low back — neutral is between these two','Every workout: activate glutes before loading'],
 array['Functional movement correction program','Athletic performance foundation posture','Sport-specific movement correction'],
 array['Passive hip flexor stretching','Glute squeeze awareness lying down','Walking with conscious posterior pelvic position'],
 array['postural','lower_crossed_syndrome','anterior_pelvic_tilt','hip_flexors','glutes','corrective'], array['spondylolisthesis_severe'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('Thoracic Kyphosis Correction',
 'rhomboids', array['lower_traps','thoracic_extensors','shoulder'], array['rhomboids','lower_traps'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['foam_roller','resistance_bands','bodyweight'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Excessive thoracic kyphosis (hunchback) correction program. (1) Foam roller thoracic extension: segmental extension over foam roller 2x60s. (2) Thoracic rotation: quadruped rotation 3x10 each side. (3) Prone Y-T-W for lower trapezius 3x12. (4) Seated row for rhomboids and lower trap 3x15. (5) Pec stretch doorway 3x45s. (6) Deep breathing into the back: forces rib cage expansion. Duration: 6-12 months for structural change.',
 'Expecting quick results (structural kyphosis takes months to change); foam rolling without the strengthening component; ignoring daily posture habits; pec stretching without lower trap strengthening (pecs will overpower).',
 'postural_rehab', array['Roll opens the joint: strengthen immediately after to hold it','Lower trap: the muscle that holds thoracic extension','Pec tightness pulls you forward: stretch it daily','12 months: structural posture changes take time — measure every 3 months'],
 array['Heavy rowing program for upper back strength','Thoracic extension loaded program','Full postural assessment re-screen at 3 months'],
 array['Passive foam rolling only','Gentle thoracic extension over a rolled towel','Seated posture awareness without movement'],
 array['postural','thoracic_kyphosis','foam_roller','rounded_back','corrective_exercise'], array['vertebral_fracture','severe_osteoporosis'],
