('Neck Pain: Cervical Stabilization Program',
 'cervical_extensors', array['deep_cervical_flexors','traps','shoulder'], array['cervical_extensors','deep_cervical_flexors'],
 'rehab', 'strength', array['resistance_bands','bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Non-specific neck pain management (most common type). (1) Deep cervical flexor (DCF) strengthening: supine chin tuck with 5s hold 3x10. (2) Cervical extension: prone head lift (small range) 3x10. (3) Cervical rotation: gentle rotation to end of range 10 each direction 3x. (4) Upper trap and levator scapulae stretching 3x30s. (5) Scapular stabilization for cervical support: band pull-apart, wall slides. (6) Ergonomic screen height adjustment.',
 'Forceful cervical manipulation without professional assessment; ignoring thoracic stiffness (cervical pain often comes from thoracic restriction); treating all neck pain as muscular (some is disc or nerve related).',
 'cervical_rehab', array['DCF: the neck''s "core" — weak in all chronic neck pain','Gentle range: pain-free exploration of movement','Thoracic first: thoracic restriction causes cervical compensation','Assessment: neck pain with arm symptoms needs imaging — see a physio'],
 array['Cervical strength progression program','Return to sport with contact','Ergonomics workstation full assessment'],
 array['Gentle neck stretching only','Heat application for muscle relaxation','Activity modification reducing neck load'],
